title: How to fool a GPS

aws-transcripts.transcript: something happened in the early morning hours of May 2nd 2000 that had a profound effect on the way our society operates. Ironically, hardly anyone noticed that the time the change was silent, imperceptible unless you knew exactly what to look for. On that morning, U S President Bill Clinton ordered that a special switch be thrown in the orbiting satellites of the global Positioning System. Instantaneously, every civilian GPS receiver around the globe went from errors the size of a football field, two errors the size of a small room. It's hard to overstate the effect that this change in accuracy has had on us before this switch was thrown, we didn't have in car navigation systems giving turn by turn directions because back then, GPS couldn't tell you what block you're on, let alone what street Fergie location, accuracy matters and things have only improved over the last 10 years, with more base stations were ground stations, better receivers and better algorithms. GPS can now not only tell you what street you're on, but what part of the street. This level of accuracy has unleashed a firestorm of innovation. In fact, many of you navigated here today with the help of your Tom Tom or your smartphone paper maps are becoming obsolete. Boys down now, stand on the verge of another revolution in geo location accuracy. What if I told you that the two meter positioning that our current tell phones and our our Tom Toms give us is pathetic compared to what we could be getting for dump? Sometime now, it's been known that if you pay attention to the carrier phase of the GPS signal and if you have an Internet connection, then you can go from meter level two centimeter level, even millimeter level position. So why don't we have this capability on our on our phones on Lee, I believe for a lack of imagination.
